<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
    Android has forbidden cleartext HTTP since API 28, and it is right to.

    But this app's fallback address is the PC on your own wifi (http://192.168.x.x:7777), and
    the wifi-only mode of "kaip serve" drops the tunnel entirely, so plain HTTP over the local
    network IS the feature. Without this, the app simply could not reach a PC on the LAN: that
    mode was one that could not possibly work, and the failure came back as an Android policy
    error that said nothing about what you had done wrong.

    It has to be allowed in general rather than for one address: the config is compiled into
    the APK, and the IP of your PC is not known until you scan the QR. Android's domain rules
    take hostnames and literal IPs, not CIDR ranges, so there is no way to say "private
    networks only" here.

    What limits the surface is not this file: it is that the app only ever talks to ONE
    address, the one inside the pairing QR, which you scanned off your own screen. And the
    tunnel is https and stays https: everything that crosses the internet is encrypted twice
    over (TLS, and the AES-256-GCM seal underneath it that Cloudflare cannot open).

    Mind the wording here: a DOUBLE HYPHEN is illegal inside an XML comment. Writing the
    wifi flag out in full, with its two leading dashes, is what made this very file fail to
    compile the day it was committed. The app could not be built at all, and since that commit
    was never released, nobody found out.
-->
<network-security-config>
    <base-config cleartextTrafficPermitted="true" />
</network-security-config>
